<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="1">
[[ 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatus">Apogon fasciatus</taxonomicName>
species group ]]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph lastPageNumber="2" pageNumber="1">
Color patterns similarities in the large genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E2B6AA3A-0463-44C8-BF33-43A19DBDA3CA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon Lacépède 1801:411" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Apogon</taxonomicName>
are used to group various species into smaller phenetic groups which may prove to be monophyletic through additional character analysis. General habitat fidelity may provide another clue to relationships. The 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" species="fasciatus">
Apogon 
<pageStartToken pageNumber="2">fasciatus</pageStartToken>
</taxonomicName>
species grouping as proposed here, has a common basis in general color pattern, a mid-lateral dark stripe from the snout to tip of the caudal fin, no dark stripes below the mid-lateral stripe, no dark spots on head or body and black stomachs. First-dorsal spines are VI and VII in this group. These species generally have a coastal shelf (continental-like) distribution, preferring sandy or muddy bottoms of deeper tropical waters or shallow warm-temperate waters. The presence of an unidentified species, often identified as 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatus">Apogon fasciatus</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BFD05E88-7993-426F-9AC5-099D155992E5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon quadrifasciatus Cuvier 1828:153" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciatus">A. quadrifasciatus</taxonomicName>
, resulted in a preliminary examination of the group by the author and Ernest A. Lachner in 1974. A review of that information during the past several years confirmed the initial conclusion about the existence of an undescribed species. The purpose of this report is to describe the new species, review the status of nominal species and provide a detailed examination of the gill raker variation among the valid species and geographically within 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatus">Apogon fasciatus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="2">
White (1790) briefly described the first species, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Mullidae" genus="Mullus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatus">Mullus fasciatus</taxonomicName>
, in this complex from southeastern Australia, but either failed to preserve the specimen or it was lost with time. The original illustration clearly showed two dark stripes along the body. Lachner (1953: 439, Pl 35A), in a footnote of a key to the species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E2B6AA3A-0463-44C8-BF33-43A19DBDA3CA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon Lacépède 1801:411" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Apogon</taxonomicName>
, created a neotype from the type locality, Port Jackson, Australia because no types were available. The neotype was not described in Lachner’s text, but the footnote refers to the previous description and figure of the same specimen by Radcliffe (1911) along with a copy of the figure from White (1790). Radcliffe (1911) did not report any gill raker counts which was partially rectified by Lachner (1953: tab. 39 &amp; 40). Randall and Lachner (1986) recounted this history without discussing 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BFD05E88-7993-426F-9AC5-099D155992E5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon quadrifasciatus Cuvier 1828:153" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciatus">Apogon quadrifasciatus</taxonomicName>
. Randall and Hoese (1988) noted that the specimen used by Lachner can be identified with 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BFD05E88-7993-426F-9AC5-099D155992E5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon quadrifasciatus Cuvier 1828:153" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciatus">Apogon quadrifasciatus</taxonomicName>
, a wide-ranging Indo-West Pacific species, and provided a table comparison of gill-raker counts for four species. The comparative material was not listed. Kuiter (1993) and Kuiter and Kozawa (1999) suggested that 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatus">Apogon fasciatus</taxonomicName>
is restricted to eastern Australia and that 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BFD05E88-7993-426F-9AC5-099D155992E5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon quadrifasciatus Cuvier 1828:153" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciatus">Apogon quadrifasciatus</taxonomicName>
is more widespread in the Indian Ocean, but not reaching past Bali, Indonesia. Gon and Randall (2003) agreed with Kuiter (1993) reversing Randall and Hoese’s previous conclusion about a different species in eastern Australia, based on postocular stripe characteristics.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="2">
Quoy and Gaimard (1825) described 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatus">Apogon fasciatus</taxonomicName>
from Guam, a preoccupied name as a secondary homonym, the result of White’s earlier name. Weber and de Beaufort (1929) listed Quoy and Gaimard’s name under 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BFDC000D-E56C-4E39-B7A2-3011ACA28F3B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon novemfasciatus Cuvier 1828:154" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="novemfasciatus">Apogon novemfasciatus Cuvier in Cuvier and Valeniecnnes, 1828</taxonomicName>
. According to Randall and Lachner (1986) Quoy and Gaimard’s holotype is 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BFDC000D-E56C-4E39-B7A2-3011ACA28F3B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon novemfasciatus Cuvier 1828:154" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="novemfasciatus">Apogon novemfasciatus</taxonomicName>
. My examination of these types leads to the same conclusion.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="2">
Cuvier in Cuvier &amp; Valenciennes (1828) described 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BFD05E88-7993-426F-9AC5-099D155992E5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon quadrifasciatus Cuvier 1828:153" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciatus">Apogon quadrifasciatus</taxonomicName>
from a single specimen taken at Pondichery, India. Comparing his specimen with the description of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatus">Apogon fasciatus (White)</taxonomicName>
, Cuvier concluded that differences existed. Weber and de Beaufort (1929:300) listed 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Mullidae" genus="Mullus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatus">Mullus fasciatus</taxonomicName>
as a questionable name with priority.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="3">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Günther">
<pageStartToken pageNumber="3">Guenther</pageStartToken>
</normalizedToken>
(1880) briefly described two species, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="monogramma">Apogon monogramma</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="septemstriatus">Apogon septemstriatus</taxonomicName>
from the Arafura Sea and provided figures (Pl. XVI, figs A &amp; B). No comparisons were made with previously described species. Weber and de Beaufort (1929:300) listed 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="monogramma">Apogon monogramma</taxonomicName>
as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BFD05E88-7993-426F-9AC5-099D155992E5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon quadrifasciatus Cuvier 1828:153" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciatus">Apogon quadrifasciatus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="3">
Fowler (1904) described 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:6CC74612-D79B-4213-AB67-C53AC8F0A6CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon evanidus Fowler 1904:518" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="evanidus">Apogon evanidus</taxonomicName>
from Padang, Sumatra, Indonesia based on two specimens. He compared this species with 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:0B4D686F-300E-48E3-A81C-6A6AB633DFDA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon fraenatus Valenciennes 1832:57" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fraenatus">Apogon fraenatus</taxonomicName>
, a species in another subgenus. Weber and de Beaufort (1929:300) listed 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:6CC74612-D79B-4213-AB67-C53AC8F0A6CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon evanidus Fowler 1904:518" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="evanidus">Apogon evanidus</taxonomicName>
as a questionable synonym of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BFD05E88-7993-426F-9AC5-099D155992E5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon quadrifasciatus Cuvier 1828:153" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciatus">Apogon quadrifasciatus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="3">
Jordan &amp; Snyder (1901) described 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF9D0872-446E-4AF0-A0F4-097E00CEC663" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon kiensis Jordan &amp; Snyder 1901:905" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kiensis">Apogon kiensis</taxonomicName>
from Wakanoura Kii, Japan. No species comparisons were made. Weber and de Beaufort (1929:302) contrasted the number of first dorsal spines in this species and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BFD05E88-7993-426F-9AC5-099D155992E5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon quadrifasciatus Cuvier 1828:153" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciatus">Apogon quadrifasciatus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="3">
Jordan &amp; Seale (1905) described 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10F095F4-F5A9-4440-B714-74BF24DFA195" class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Amia elizabethae Jordan &amp; Seale 1905:9" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="elizabethae">Amia elizabethae</taxonomicName>
from Hong Kong, China. No species comparisons were made. Jordan and Richardson (1909) noted that 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10F095F4-F5A9-4440-B714-74BF24DFA195" class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Amia elizabethae Jordan &amp; Seale 1905:9" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="elizabethae">A. elizabethae</taxonomicName>
was very close to 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciata">A. quadrifasciata</taxonomicName>
. Fowler (1937) synonomized 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10F095F4-F5A9-4440-B714-74BF24DFA195" class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Amia elizabethae Jordan &amp; Seale 1905:9" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="elizabethae">Amia elizabethae</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciata">Amia quadrifasciata</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="3">
Regan (1908) described 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7D42D1E8-CC9E-4078-9F17-67E4226FD86D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon quinquestriatus Regan 1908:226" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quinquestriatus">Apogon quinquestriatus</taxonomicName>
from South Nilandu, Maldive Islands. He related this species to 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BFD05E88-7993-426F-9AC5-099D155992E5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon quadrifasciatus Cuvier 1828:153" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciatus">Apogon quadrifasciatus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="septemstriatus">A. septemstriatus</taxonomicName>
. No other material has been reported.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="3">
McCulloch (1915) created new name combinations in 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Amia</taxonomicName>
based on White’s name treating one new subspecies and three other color forms as polychromic subspecies: 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="fasciata" subSpecies="fasciata">Amia fasciata fasciata</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="fasciata" subSpecies="aroubiensis">A. f. aroubiensis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="fasciata" subSpecies="compressa">A. f. compressa</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="fasciata" subSpecies="novemfasciata">A. f. novemfasciata</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A5F9E97C-4591-4CB0-8511-D0CCC7E1D631" class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Amia fasciata stevensi McCulloch 1915:118" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="fasciata" subSpecies="stevensi">A. f. stevensi</taxonomicName>
. None of the subspecies combinations has survived as useful taxa. McCulloch listed 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="monogramma">Apogon monogramma</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF9D0872-446E-4AF0-A0F4-097E00CEC663" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon kiensis Jordan &amp; Snyder 1901:905" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kiensis">Apogon kiensis</taxonomicName>
as synonyms of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciata">Amia quadrifasciata</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="3">
Fowler and Bean (1930) listed 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="monogramma">Apogon monogramma</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10F095F4-F5A9-4440-B714-74BF24DFA195" class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Amia elizabethae Jordan &amp; Seale 1905:9" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="elizabethae">Amia elizabethae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7D42D1E8-CC9E-4078-9F17-67E4226FD86D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon quinquestriatus Regan 1908:226" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quinquestriatus">Apogon quinquestriatus</taxonomicName>
as synonyms of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciata">Amia quadrifasciata</taxonomicName>
. The species they treated as 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Amiidae" genus="Amia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amiiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciata">Amia fasciata</taxonomicName>
was a combination of other dark-striped species. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF9D0872-446E-4AF0-A0F4-097E00CEC663" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon kiensis Jordan &amp; Snyder 1901:905" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kiensis">Apogon kiensis</taxonomicName>
was treated as a separate species described with VII first-dorsal spines instead of VI and was misidentified.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="3">
J.L.B. Smith (1961) was the first to report on specimens, identified as 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF9D0872-446E-4AF0-A0F4-097E00CEC663" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon kiensis Jordan &amp; Snyder 1901:905" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kiensis">Apogon kiensis</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:58F5E86D-3FF3-4BC8-87E9-E595BCD6E006" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon bryx Fraser 1998:987" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bryx">Apogon bryx</taxonomicName>
), from various locations in the Indian Ocean (Red Sea and Mozambique). All other prior reports he mentioned, Jordan &amp; Snyder (1901), Seale (1914) and Fowler &amp; Bean (1930), were from Japan, China and the Philippines. Some of these reports were based on a VII spined species, identified as as 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BFD05E88-7993-426F-9AC5-099D155992E5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon quadrifasciatus Cuvier 1828:153" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadrifasciatus">Apogon quadrifasciatus</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatus">A. fasciatus</taxonomicName>
, either due to trawl damaged first spine or overlooking the tiny first dorsal spine. Data presented here from examination of the type material of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF9D0872-446E-4AF0-A0F4-097E00CEC663" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon kiensis Jordan &amp; Snyder 1901:905" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kiensis">Apogon kiensis</taxonomicName>
from Japan and material reported by Smith (1961) revealed gill raker count and slight pectoral-fin ray differences of a then undescribed species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="4" pageNumber="3">
Fraser (1998) described 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:58F5E86D-3FF3-4BC8-87E9-E595BCD6E006" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon bryx Fraser 1998:987" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bryx">Apogon bryx</taxonomicName>
from Balayan Bay, Luzon Island Philippines from one specimen taken in 145-155 m. He compared this species with other VI spined species and concluded that 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:58F5E86D-3FF3-4BC8-87E9-E595BCD6E006" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon bryx Fraser 1998:987" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bryx">A. bryx</taxonomicName>
was related to a possible new species from the western Indian Ocean and to 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF9D0872-446E-4AF0-A0F4-097E00CEC663" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon kiensis Jordan &amp; Snyder 1901:905" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kiensis">A. kiensis</taxonomicName>
. Data presented here shows that 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF9D0872-446E-4AF0-A0F4-097E00CEC663" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon kiensis Jordan &amp; Snyder 1901:905" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kiensis">Apogon kiensis</taxonomicName>
is restricted 
<pageStartToken pageNumber="4">to</pageStartToken>
the East China Sea and Japan, while 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:58F5E86D-3FF3-4BC8-87E9-E595BCD6E006" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Apogon bryx Fraser 1998:987" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bryx">Apogon bryx</taxonomicName>
is widespread from the Red Sea (see Gon and Randall, 2003) to Taiwan and the Philippines.
</paragraph>
